<TITLE> 'Wake up to the rights of women' </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, March 8 (bdnews24.com)  The country marks International Women's Day Saturday, which is being observed round the world with the theme of "investing in women and girls". Transparency International, Bangladesh and the Anticorruption Commission have jointly organised a concert for Saturday to mark the day, to be held at Gulshan Youth Club from 2:00pm to 9:00pm. The concert to carry the slogan"Wake Up People, Wake Up to the Rights of Women"aims both at establishing women's rights and inspiring people against corruption linking the movements against corruption with women's rights. On March 8, 1857 women workers in the US garments industry staged protests demanding shorter working hours, pay raises and better working conditions. They were successful in lowering their working hours from 12 hours to eight hours. In 1910, German socialist Clara Zetkin proposed observing the day as International Women's Day, which the world has been doing ever since. Various national organisations have chalked out detailed plans to mark the day including seminars, rallies, concerts and cultural programmes. Bangladesh Mahila Parishad staged a colourful rally around 9:00 am from the National Museum carrying placards and festoons. President Iajuddin Ahmed and chief adviser Fakhruddin Ahmed in separate statements praised women's roles in society. The chief adviser in a message to mark the occasion said the participation of women alongside men is essential for a strong and constant development. "Women of the country are equal partners in every sphere of economic and social development." The president said in his message said the country must ensure women's participation and their rights in every sphere of national activities. Sammilito Nari Samaj, Jatiya Nari Jote, Jatiya Garments Sramik Federation, Bangladesh Institute of Labour Studies, Karmajibi Nari, Shilpakala Academy, Bangladesh International Film Movement, among other organizations, are observing the day with their own programmes. bd